There are many who think that our politicians are incapable of subtlety and finesse in any shape or form. They are woefully mistaken.
Criticisms
What Mheshimiwa meant in that most decorous of criticisms is that the state machinery deployed to popularise the BBI has terrorised Kenyans and otherwise comported itself in such odious and tyrannical ways, Kenyans were all but ready to consign the proposals to the dustbin if a referendum were held. He also meant to say that introducing civil servants into competitive or contested political activity is not only singularly unwise, it guarantees spectacularly disastrous outcomes.
Ideally, civil servants are required to scrupulously signal political neutrality, and cultivate public confidence on their impartiality at all times. Civil servants are trained to be deliberately staid, to eschew drama and flee controversy at all costs.
Government authority considerably depends on the credibility of its public servants, who must embody the gravity of their office and the solemnity of the service.



