 Kenyans are grievously afflicted by a recent unfortunate turn in our public affairs. It is now commonplace for civil servants to engage in partisan political competition. It is also normal for them to be boastful, arrogant and menacing, as though doing their best to undermine government agenda in the name of advancing it.
A number of them are considered active contenders for various national and devolved elective positions, and have not been shy in displaying their campaign assets.
Legitimacy
Consequently, the effectiveness, legitimacy and credibility of government has taken a severe beating.
Many Kenyans neither consider nor expect the civil service to be fair, impartial or neutral in its undertakings. In addition to the sorry blemishes of tribalism, nepotism and runaway graft, shameless politicking is the latest blight.
Vital public services like the administration of law and order, provision of security, implementation of development projects and disbursement of public resources are no longer deemed to be fairly arbitrated by disinterested servants of the people. Instead, they are viewed to be rewards or punishments meted out on the basis of favouritism or vindictiveness.



