Nowadays, few government projects proceed without the obligatory demolition, arson, cruel displacement of vulnerable people in desperately inclement weather and the liberal deployment of savage violence on fellow citizens.
Clearly, considerations like adequate notice, provision of alternative amenities and humane treatment are foreign to government thinking.
These civil servants are supposed to persuade Kenyans to support BBI, or to trust that the Huduma Namba is not some diabolical subterfuge, or that the draconian pandemic containment measures are actually in their interest.
Crackdown
This cohort of brash, swaggering and sneering civil servants fills Kenyans with dread. Every way a citizen turns, there is a deadline, or ban, or ultimatum that constrains her agency and limits her freedom.
The preferred vocabulary of contemporary public service bristles with “Starting today... mpende msipende…” and the all-time favourite: “…failure to which…”
It is a lamentable inventory of crackdowns (by multi-agency teams, of course), marufuku and every manner of dire administrative injustice.
Without a doubt, the clique of swashbuckling bureaucrats consider haunting Kenyans to be the stuff of government, and publicly relish their unpleasantness.



